            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> I don't think running one off runs or even using tools like hyperfine is very representative of real world. You also can't just consider hot runs; cold runs matter too and are the most noticeable and impacting when they are noticeably slow.\r\n\r\nI don't know what \"hot/cold runs\" mean here, but I think that is the point of caching dark magic: you add it to the top of the 'init.lua', run once to cache, and enjoy faster startup happily ever after.\r\n\r\nRunning `nvim --startuptime nvim.log` three times with (after initial caching) and three times without `vim.loader.enable()` at the top reduced startup (the number in `--- NVIM STARTED ---` line) by about 30% for me. From ~95ms to ~70ms in my personal non-lazy loaded version of a config and from ~137ms to ~99ms in [someone else's config](https://bsky.app/profile/echasnovski.com/post/3mgxeqdyl3c2y).",
            "created_at": "2026-03-16T19:31:01Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/38321#issuecomment-4070075698",
            "id": 4070075698,
            "issue_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/neovim/neovim/issues/38321",
            "node_id": "IC_kwDOAPphoM7ymG0y",
            "performed_via_github_app": null,
            "reactions": {
