        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> I don't know what \"hot/cold runs\" mean here, but I think that is the point of caching dark magic: you add it to the top of the 'init.lua', run once to cache, and enjoy faster startup happily ever after.\r\n\r\nOnce you've started Neovim once, you've already changed the state of the machine quite a bit. The Lua bytecode cache may be warm, but so is the OS page cache, directory lookups, shared libraries, and whatever else got pulled in during startup. By the second and third run you’re measuring a different environment than the first one, so it's hard to attribute the difference specifically to vim.loader.\r\n\r\nThat also makes the sample size a problem. Three runs is enough to show \"I can see a difference on my machine\", but not really enough to support a broader claim about the feature. Startup time at this scale moves around a lot depending on system load, CPU frequency, background I/O, and the particular config being used.\r\n\r\nSo I don't doubt the numbers you saw, but I do think they’re describing one very specific warmed-up case rather than giving a reliable picture of the overall impact. If we want to argue that vim.loader is worth the complexity, I think we need more than a few sequential launches after the machine has already been primed by earlier runs. This is exactly why I've been collecting these stats on my machines over the last few months, as it avoids these kinds of factors that can skew results.\r\n",
